The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface that represents an HTML document as a tree structure of objects. JavaScript uses the DOM to dynamically access, change, style, and manipulate webpage content.

1. Accessing HTML Elements (Selection)
Before you can manipulate an element, you need to select it from the DOM tree. Modern JavaScript provides several robust methods:

A. Core Selector Methods
document.getElementById('id'): Targets a single element matching the unique ID string.

document.getElementsByClassName('className'): Targets all elements matching the class name. Returns an HTMLCollection.

document.getElementsByTagName('tagName'): Targets elements matching the HTML tag name (e.g., 'p', 'div'). Returns an HTMLCollection.

document.querySelector('selector'): Returns the very first element that matches a specified CSS selector (e.g., '.class', '#id', 'div > p').

document.querySelectorAll('selector'): Returns a static NodeList containing all matching elements.

JavaScript
// Selecting by CSS selector
let mainHeading = document.querySelector('#main-title');
let listItems = document.querySelectorAll('.nav-item');
2. Updating Elements (Content & Styles)
Once an element is accessed, its content or layout properties can be updated dynamically.

A. Updating Content
.innerHTML: Fetches or sets text content along with its internal HTML tags parsed.

.textContent: Fetches or sets raw text content exactly as it is written in the source code, ignoring HTML tags.

.innerText: Fetches or sets visible text content as it appears rendered on the screen (respects CSS visibility).

JavaScript
let container = document.querySelector('.box');

container.innerHTML = "<h2>New Heading</h2>"; // Parsed as a heading element
container.textContent = "<h2>New Heading</h2>"; // Rendered as plain text strings
B. Updating Styles & Attributes
.style.property: Edits inline CSS styles dynamically (uses camelCase properties like backgroundColor).

.setAttribute(name, value): Adds or overrides HTML attributes safely.

.classList.add() / .classList.remove() / .classList.toggle(): Manages CSS classes cleanly without overriding existing ones.

JavaScript
let button = document.querySelector('.btn');
button.style.backgroundColor = "blue"; // Updates inline style
button.classList.add('active');       // Appends a utility CSS class
3. Inserting New Elements (Creation & Placement)
Adding new elements to a page involves two main architectural steps: Creating the element floating in memory, and Appending it somewhere inside the live DOM tree structure.

A. Creating Elements
document.createElement('tagName'): Generates a brand new element node in the background memory.

B. Inserting Elements into the Tree
parent.appendChild(child): Adds the child element as the very last child node inside the targeted parent element.

parent.insertBefore(newNode, referenceNode): Injects the newNode directly before a specific referenceNode inside the parent wrapper.

.insertAdjacentHTML(position, text): Injects raw HTML code string data into specific relative spatial positions:

'beforebegin': Directly before the target element itself.

'afterbegin': Inside the element, before its first child node.

'beforeend': Inside the element, after its last child node.

'afterend': Directly after the target element itself.

JavaScript
// Step 1: Creation
let newParagraph = document.createElement('p');
newParagraph.textContent = "This is dynamically appended text!";

// Step 2: Placement
let dynamicContainer = document.querySelector('.content-wrapper');
dynamicContainer.appendChild(newParagraph); // Inserts paragraph at the bottom
4. Deleting Elements (Removal)
Removing outdated components keeps web applications clean and optimized.

parent.removeChild(child): Removes a specific child node from a targeted parent container. (Older way).

element.remove(): Removes the element directly from the DOM tree on its own. (Modern, clean way).

JavaScript
let temporaryBanner = document.querySelector('.promo-banner');

// Direct self-removal
temporaryBanner.remove();
💡 Production Best Practices
Minimize Reflows: Avoid appending elements inside a loop one by one using .appendChild(). This forces the browser to re-render the layout repeatedly. Instead, stack elements into a temporary virtual placeholder container called a DocumentFragment, and append that fragment to the live DOM tree in a single operation.

Prefer classList Over Inline Styles: Instead of writing detailed inline layout strings like element.style.color = 'red', create a dedicated .error-text utility class in your CSS file and simply append it using element.classList.add('error-text').

When a user interacts with a webpage—whether by clicking a button, typing inside an input box, or scrolling down a page—the browser generates an Event. JavaScript can listen for these events and execute a specific block of code (a callback function) in response.1. What is an Event Listener?An event listener is an engine mechanic attached to a DOM element that waits patiently for a specific user action to occur.The Old Way (Inline/Property Event Handlers)JavaScriptlet btn = document.querySelector('.btn');
btn.onclick = function() {
    console.log("Clicked!");
};
The Problem: You can only assign one function to an event property at a time. If you write another btn.onclick lower down, it overrides the first one completely.The Modern Way: addEventListener()This method allows you to attach multiple operations to a single event on an element safely.$$\mathbf{\text{element.addEventListener('eventType', callbackFunction)}}$$JavaScriptlet btn = document.querySelector('.btn');

const alertUser = () => console.log("Button Hovered!");
const logData = () => console.log("Tracking analytics...");

// Attaching multiple operations to the same event pipeline safely
btn.addEventListener('mouseenter', alertUser);
btn.addEventListener('mouseenter', logData);
2. Common Event TypesCategoryEvent NameCore Trigger MechanicMouse'click'Fires when an element is clicked.'dblclick'Fires when an element is double-clicked.'mouseenter'Fires when the mouse pointer moves onto an element.Keyboard'keydown'Fires the instant a key on the keyboard is pressed down.'keyup'Fires when a pressed key is released.Form'submit'Fires when a form is submitted (attached to the <form> element).'change'Fires when the value of an input element changes (e.g., dropdown select).3. The Event Object (e)When an event fires, the browser automatically passes an Event Object as an argument into your callback function. This object holds valuable data footprints about the interaction:JavaScriptlet inputField = document.querySelector('#username');

inputField.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    console.log(`Key pressed: ${e.key}`);  // The literal character typed (e.g., "A")
    console.log(`Key code: ${e.code}`);    // The physical key coordinate (e.g., "KeyA")
});
Stopping Default Behaviors: e.preventDefault()Some elements have built-in default browser behaviors. For example, clicking a link automatically navigates to a URL, and submitting a form automatically refreshes the entire page. You can intercept and block this using e.preventDefault():JavaScriptlet form = document.querySelector('#signup-form');

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault(); // 🛑 Stops the page from reloading!
    console.log("Form data harvested via AJAX instead.");
});
4. Event Lifecycle: Bubbling vs. CapturingWhen an event triggers on an element nested deep inside other elements, it travels through the DOM tree. This travel lifecycle happens in two phase architectures:A. Event Bubbling (Default)The event triggers first on the target element that was explicitly clicked, and then bubbles upward through its parent ancestors like an air bubble in water.JavaScript// If you click a button inside a <div>, the button's click fires first, then the <div>'s click
btn.addEventListener('click', () => console.log("Button Clicked")); 
Stopping Propagation: If you want an event to fire only on the child and not trigger its parent containers, call e.stopPropagation():JavaScriptbtn.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    e.stopPropagation(); // 🛑 Stops the event bubble from rising upward
    console.log("Only the button fires.");
});
B. Event CapturingThe exact inverse of bubbling. The event trickles downward from the highest global window layer down to the target element. To listen to an event during the capturing phase instead of bubbling, pass an optional third parameter { capture: true } inside your listener setup.5. Performance Optimization: Event DelegationIf you have an un-ordered list (<ul>) containing 1,000 list items (<li>), attaching an individual .addEventListener() to every single list item creates massive performance lag and wastes system memory.Instead, leverage Event Bubbling using Event Delegation. Attach one single listener to the parent <ul>, and let clicks bubble up to it.JavaScriptlet parentList = document.querySelector('#global-list');

parentList.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    // Check if the actual clicked item target is an <li> element
    if (e.target.tagName === 'LI') {
        console.log(`Item contents: ${e.target.textContent}`);
    }
});
💡 Production Best PracticesClean Up Memory Loops: If you are building single-page applications (SPAs) where components mount and unmount dynamically, always remove event listeners using element.removeEventListener('type', functionName) when destroying elements to prevent application memory leaks.Avoid Inline Scripts: Keep your HTML markup clean. Never map execution code straight into markup templates like <button onclick="alert('run')">. Isolate all interaction pipelines inside your script layers.